-Nnxz_Hm8iihWub1rm5d.description: Kachori Chaat: Ayodhya's Savory Explosion in Every Bite Ayodhya's culinary tapestry wouldn't be complete without Kachori Chaat, a symphony of textures and flavors that tantalizes every taste bud. These deep-fried, golden-hued dumplings burst open with a savory filling, then get dressed in a vibrant ensemble of chutneys, spices, and crunchy toppings. Here's what makes this chaat experience unique and where you can find it in Ayodhya:  The Kachori Delights:  Kachoris are Ayodhya's beloved street food staple. Made with a flaky maida or atta dough, they're stuffed with spiced lentil (moong dal or urad dal) fillings or a potato masala, offering a range of delicious options. The deep-frying lends a satisfying crunch to the exterior, while the filling delivers bursts of warm spice and hearty goodness. The Chaat Transformation:  This is where the magic happens! Kachoris are broken into bite-sized pieces, creating a bed for a vibrant medley of chutneys. Sweet mango chutney adds a tangy contrast, while the fiery green chutney brings a welcome spice kick. Yogurt cools down the heat, while chopped onions and coriander leaves add freshness and textural contrast. Toasted spices like cumin and black pepper dance on the palate, and a sprinkle of crunchy sev completes the symphony of flavors. Where to Find Your Kachori Nirvana:  Every corner of Ayodhya boasts stalls and small eateries offering Kachori Chaat, but some stand out from the crowd: Ram Katha Park: The park's bustling food stalls serve up some of the city's best Kachori Chaat, perfect for a pre- or post-sightseeing treat. Chowk Bazaar: This vibrant market street is a haven for street food, and its Kachori Chaat vendors are masters of the craft. Param Sweets: This renowned sweet shop surprisingly offers a delightful Kachori Chaat, making it a must-try for sweet and savory enthusiasts. Beyond the Kachori:  While Kachori Chaat is the star of the show, exploring other chaat variations like Samosa Chaat and Aloo Tikki Chaat is also recommended. Each offers a unique blend of textures and flavors, showcasing the diversity of Ayodhya's street food scene. A Bite-Sized Pilgrimage:  No trip to Ayodhya is complete without experiencing the fiery delight of Kachori Chaat. So, dive into the colorful chaos of flavors, let the crispy kachoris and vibrant chutneys dance on your tongue, and discover why this humble street food holds a special place in Ayodhya's culinary heart.
-Nnxz_Hm8iihWub1rm5d.name: Kachori Chat

Here's a glimpse into the delectable world of Ayodhya's Rabri:   A Symphony of Milk and Time:  Rabri is the epitome of slow-cooked indulgence. Fresh, full-cream milk is simmered for hours, gently coaxed into a thick, golden elixir. Time plays a crucial role, allowing the milk solids to caramelize and intensify the flavors. The subtle heat concentrates the milk's natural sweetness, while gentle stirring prevents scorching and creates a silken texture. Each bubble rising during the slow dance of heat and time hints at the impending decadence. Cardamom's aromatic whispers add a floral complexity, while a hint of nutmeg or saffron warms the palate and adds depth. Some prefer a touch of rosewater for a delicate floral note, while others relish the earthy richness of chopped nuts like pistachios or almonds. Each variation offers a unique journey for the senses.

This creamy rice pudding isn't just a dessert; it's a comforting hug in a bowl, a warm embrace of tradition, and a taste of the city's rich culinary heritage. Let's dive into the sweet world of Ayodhya's Kheer:   A Symphony of Rice and Milk:   The heart of Kheer lies in its simplicity. Mothers pass down generations-old recipes, simmering it with love in clay pots for family gatherings. Traditional sweet shops like Maurya Mishthan Bhandar and Guptaji Sweets offer their own delectable versions, beautifully adorned and ready to indulge.

-Nnx2PH-U4nohV9vk0-y.description: In the homeland of Lord Rama, Ayodhya, Tulsi Smarak Bhavan Museum is one of the major tourist attractions of Uttar Pradesh. Dedicated to Goswami Tulsidas, Tulsi Smarak Bhavan Museum was established in the year 1969. Tulsidas was a great Hindu poet who penned down the Hindu epic, Ramacharitramanas and Hanuman Chalisa. Coming on to this popular museum in Ayodhya, it houses a large repository of Tulsidas literary compositions. Not just this, the museum is also known for hosting devotional concerts, prayer meetings and religious discourses. In the complex of the Tulsi Smarak Bhavan, there is also a research centre known as Ayodhya Shodh Sansthan. Along with that, this must-visit place in Ayodhya also includes a library which features a great exhibition of Ramayana art and craft and recitation of Ram Katha. Apart from all this, one of the major highlights of Tulsi Smarak Bhavan Museum is the year-round enactment of Ram Leela. It is performed daily from 6:00 PM to 9:00 PM.

This is the sacred place where Lord Sri Vishnu himself incarnated in human form and performed his pastimes. The history of this mythical city is very sacred. In this sacred city, Sugriva Fort, located near the Ram Jambhumi complex, is a very historical and mythical place in itself, where all enemies are destroyed with a single glance. This ancient fort was built at Tretayuga by Maharaja Bharata to welcome Lord Sri Ram back to Ayodhya after his conquest of Lanka. Later, Lord Sri Ram, the king of Ayodhya, gave this place to Maharaja Sugriva to stay in Ayodhya. -Nnx9Uc691mb1-7NhwRA.description: Sita Kund, located in Ayodhya, is a revered site associated with the Hindu epic Ramayana and the life of Goddess Sita, the consort of Lord Rama. This sacred pond holds great significance in Hindu mythology and is believed to be the spot where Sita, according to the Ramayana, emerged from the earth as a child.  The legend goes that King Janaka, the father of Sita, was plowing the field when he found a beautiful baby girl in the furrow. Considering her a divine blessing, he named her Sita, and she grew up to become the central character in the epic Ramayana.  Sita Kund is a tranquil and serene water body, surrounded by lush greenery, creating a peaceful atmosphere. Pilgrims and devotees visit this site to pay homage to Goddess Sita and to witness the place where, according to the legend, she was found by King Janaka.  The pond is often considered a symbol of purity, and many believe that taking a dip in its waters can cleanse the soul and bring blessings. Devotees participate in rituals and prayers at Sita Kund, seeking the divine grace of Goddess Sita for happiness, prosperity, and familial harmony.  The spiritual and cultural significance of Sita Kund adds to the overall religious landscape of Ayodhya. Pilgrims, tourists, and believers come to this sacred site to connect with the mythology and immerse themselves in the sacredness of the place. Sita Kund, with its historical and religious importance, continues to be a place of reverence and devotion in the hearts of those who visit Ayodhya.
-Nnx9Uc691mb1-7NhwRA.name: Sita Kund

-NnxSqKJm0OP5m-DNpyr.description: At a distance of 3 km from Ayodhya Junction, Mani Parvat is a tiny hillock situated in Kami Ganj, Ayodhya. It is one of the popular religious places to visit in Ayodhya.  Situated about 65 feet above sea level, Mani Parvat has a great religious significance. According to Ramayana, Lord Hanuman uprooted an entire mountain containing the rejuvenating sanjeevani booti to treat Lakshman who was wounded in a battle by Meghnath. It is believed that a part of the mountain fell at a place in Ayodhya which is called Mani Parbat. It lies close to another mound called Sugriv Parbat.  Listed among the most revered places in significance to Lord Ram, Mani Parvat is home to numerous shrines. It is believed that Lord Buddha stayed in Ayodhya for six years and gave his sermons about the Law of Dharma from Mani Parbat. The hillock also houses a stupa built by Emperor Ashoka and a Buddhist monastery. One can get a spectacular view of the city of Ayodhya and the surrounding areas from the top of the hillock. There is an Islamic mausoleum at the foothills of Mani Parbat.
-NnxSqKJm0OP5m-DNpyr.name: Mani Parvat

Perched atop a hillock, Hanuman Garhi is a prominent landmark in Ayodhya and holds immense religious significance.  The temple is known for its distinctive and impressive architecture. The main deity, Lord Hanuman, is enshrined in a sitting posture within the temple complex. Devotees believe that visiting Hanuman Garhi and seeking the blessings of Lord Hanuman brings strength, courage, and protection from adversities.  The approach to Hanuman Garhi involves climbing a flight of stairs that lead to the temple premises. The panoramic view of Ayodhya from the hill adds to the spiritual experience, creating a serene and peaceful ambiance for devotees. The temple complex also includes smaller shrines dedicated to various gods and goddesses.  Devotees and pilgrims from different parts of the country visit Hanuman Garhi to offer prayers, especially on Tuesdays and Saturdays, considered auspicious for worshiping Lord Hanuman. The temple's sanctity is further enhanced by the presence of priests who conduct regular rituals and ceremonies.  Hanuman Garhi is not only a place of worship but also a symbol of unwavering devotion and faith. The temple has played a significant role in Ayodhya's cultural and religious landscape, attracting devotees, tourists, and spiritual seekers alike. The vibrant atmosphere during religious festivals, coupled with the spiritual aura of the temple, makes Hanuman Garhi a must-visit destination for those seeking solace and divine blessings in Ayodhya.
-NnwoXzfIxnoHcKniTKY.name: Hanuman Garhi

-Nnwr8mM-HqTbHAQ9NDc.description: The Ram Mandir, situated in Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh, India, holds profound significance in Hinduism as a revered religious site. This sacred temple is dedicated to Lord Ram, a central figure in the Hindu epic, Ramayana. The construction of the Ram Mandir is rooted in a historical and cultural context that spans several centuries.  The history of the site is marked by a long-standing dispute and legal battles over the ownership and use of the land. The controversy reached a significant milestone in 2019 when the Supreme Court of India delivered a verdict, granting permission for the construction of a temple dedicated to Lord Ram at the disputed site. This decision paved the way for the construction of the Ram Mandir, fulfilling the aspirations of millions of Hindus.  The architectural design of the Ram Mandir combines traditional elements with modern aesthetics, showcasing intricate carvings, sculptures, and ornate details that reflect the rich heritage of Hindu art and culture. The temple complex is designed to be a sprawling and serene space that accommodates the spiritual needs of devotees.  The sanctum sanctorum of the Ram Mandir houses the main deity, Lord Ram, along with his consort Sita, brother Lakshman, and devoted follower Hanuman. The temple is intended to serve as a center for religious and cultural activities, fostering a sense of community and devotion among its visitors.  Pilgrims and tourists alike are drawn to the Ram Mandir not only for its religious significance but also for the historical and cultural importance attached to the site. The construction and completion of the Ram Mandir stand as a symbol of unity, faith, and the shared cultural heritage of the people of India. As a beacon of spirituality, the Ram Mandir in Ayodhya continues to inspire devotion and reverence among millions of Hindus worldwide.
-Nnwr8mM-HqTbHAQ9NDc.name: Ram Janmabhoomi

Kanak Bhawan thus becomes a testament to architectural brilliance and a sublime setting for experiencing the divine presence of Lord Ram and Sita.

-NnwuzCSKuqzejF0Llq5.description: Believed to be Sita's kitchen, now a shrine and pilgrimage site. Description: Situated on the north-western side of the Ram Janmanhoomi in Ayodhya's Rajkot, Sita ki Rasoi is believed to be an ancient kitchen used by goddess Sita herself. Built quite close to the Ram Janmabhoomi, this sacred site is now a temple housing some exhibit vessels. One among the two kitchens revered in Sita's name, this Sita Ki Rasoi is a basement kitchen. The other end of the temple cites the richly clothed and embellished idols of Ram, Lakshman, Bharat and Shatrughan and their wives Sita, Urmila, Mandavi and Srutakirti. Worshipped as the Goddess of Food, Sita is also known as Goddess Annapurna. Thus, the temple follows this tradition by offering free food. Visitors can also donate any amount of money for charity here.
-NnwuzCSKuqzejF0Llq5.name: Sita Ki Rasoi

-NnwxcIhIZd5VmbgAlKy.description: Swarg Dwar, also known as Swargadwar or Swargadwar Temple, is a sacred site in Ayodhya with deep-rooted cultural and religious significance. The name "Swarg Dwar" translates to the "Gateway to Heaven," signifying its importance in Hindu mythology and beliefs.  This revered site is associated with the Hindu epic Ramayana and is believed to be the spot where Lord Rama, the seventh avatar of Lord Vishnu, is said to have left his mortal coil and entered heaven. According to the scriptures, it is believed that Swarg Dwar marks the celestial gateway through which Lord Rama ascended to his divine abode.  The temple complex is a pilgrimage destination and a place of worship for devotees. It is characterized by its spiritual ambiance and architectural elements that reflect the rich cultural heritage of Ayodhya. Pilgrims visiting Swarg Dwar often engage in prayers, rituals, and ceremonies, seeking blessings and divine intervention.  The significance of Swarg Dwar is not only religious but also cultural, as it embodies the deep-rooted connection between Lord Rama and the city of Ayodhya. The temple attracts devotees, tourists, and spiritual seekers who come to pay their respects and immerse themselves in the spiritual energy of the place.  The architecture of Swarg Dwar, along with its religious importance, contributes to the overall sanctity of Ayodhya. The site is often bustling with activity, especially during religious festivals and significant events related to Lord Rama. Swarg Dwar stands as a testament to the enduring legacy of Ayodhya as a sacred city in Hinduism.
-NnwxcIhIZd5VmbgAlKy.name: Shri vaidehi Vallabh kunj Vaman mandir swarg dwar ayodhya

-NnwyOsm5NBEsk8VsZDV.address: R626+53F, Rani Bazar Colony, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-NnwyOsm5NBEsk8VsZDV.description: Sri Mani Ram Das Chhawni or Chhoti Chhawni ( small cant ) is very famous place in Ayodhya especially after Ram Janm Bhumi dispute. The now Mahant Sri Nritya Gopal Das took an active role in the Ayodhya movement and is still active about Hindu issues. This temple has two mansions facing each other. This is the old one and in its front is the new grand building in white marble. Its central hall is huge and some 30 feet high. This building is named Walmiki bhawan, named after Maharshi Walmiki, the author of epic Ramayana. Entire Walmiki Ramayana is inscribed on the walls of its two floors. Idols of Lav and Kush, two sons of Lord Ram, with their Guru Walmiki are set at one end of the central hall.
-NnwyOsm5NBEsk8VsZDV.name: ManiRam Das Chawani / Valmiki Bhawan / Chhoti Chawani

-NnwzpsUnsQsHiYfV4N_.address: Q6W2+FP4, Tulsi Nagar, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-NnwzpsUnsQsHiYfV4N_.description: One of the oldest temples in Ayodhya, dedicated to Lord Vishnu. Description: To understand the grandeur of this temple you have to take help of a little bit of imagination. Only then you will appreciate that what was the importance of this massive complex which now takes the form of a temple. But many many years ago when the rulers of the solar dynasty had their palaces in Ayodhya, this was the entry point for the subjects to come and meet their king on official business. Like all entrances to palace complex, this one too was massive and served as the first landmark on their way to meet the King of Kosala. Raj Dwar literally translates to entry or door way to the Raj. This would have been the place outside which common people queued to get themselves checked before entering the complex walls. People must be coming and camping outside this Dwar and sometimes would spend days trying to enter. At times due to some known official entry would be easy. Or if you are an important person and have been invited by the king himself or someone from the royal family. In those days meeting the king or even having a glimpse of the king was a rarity. Amongst all that this place must have stood as the first tower which all people at that time used to look at. Today this place is converted to a mandir and residential complex seen from outside. I read somewhere that this temple is open once a year, but that is not the case. It is open on all days, only difference being that it is not on the usual tourist circuit. But the architectural marvel stands testimony to the fact that ancient Indians were master builders.
-NnwzpsUnsQsHiYfV4N_.name: Raja Dwar Mandir

-Nnx-g7R7JPA_a_ndK9F.address: R654+3V7, Theri Bazar, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-Nnx-g7R7JPA_a_ndK9F.description: A popular attraction in Ayodhya, the treta-ke-thakur Temple is dedicated to Lord Rama, who is referred to as the Lord of the Treta Yug (second out of the four yugas or ages of mankind, as per Hinduism). Located at Ayodhya's Naya Ghat, the temple was built by the king of Kullu 300 years ago and continues to draw devotees in large numbers. The temple holds immense religious significance. Legend has it that it was here that Lord Rama had conducted the 'Ashwadmedha Yagya' to celebrate his victory over Ravana. The temple houses idols of Lord Rama, Goddess Sita, Lord Lakshmana, Lord Hanuman and other important mythological deities from the epic, Ramayana. These have been carved out of a single block of black stone. The best time to visit the temple is during the Hindu calendar month of Kartik (October-November), when the temple is flocked by devotees on the eleventh day of the month Ekadashi.
-Nnx-g7R7JPA_a_ndK9F.name: Tretanath Mandir / Treta Ke Thakur
-Nnx-g7R7JPA_a_ndK9F.timings: Opens for the devotees only once a year on Kartik Shukla Ekadashi which falls in the month of October or November.

-Nnx0J0E3vtsB66xbYCj.description: Situated on the banks of River Saryu, Guptar Ghat holds immense religious significance. According to legend, this was the place where Lord Rama had taken his last dip (jal samadhi) to leave the earth and go back to his original abode 'Vaikunta'. It is a popular belief among devotees that taking a dip in the Saryu river on this ghat will wash away their sins and relieve them from worldly worries. The ghat resounds with the chants of Lord Rama's name as devotees and priests sing hymns in his praises. Tourists can also visit Raja Mandir and Chakra Harji Vishnu Temple located near Guptar Ghat, which is lined with temples of Ram Janki, Charan Paduka, Narasingh and Lord Hanuman. The well-maintained ghats were built by Raja Darshan Singh during the first half of the 19th century.
-Nnx0J0E3vtsB66xbYCj.name: Guptar Ghat

-Nnx1Dorpn2nNEWl5-vC.description: Ram ki Paidi is a series of ghats on the bank of Saryu river in Ayodhya in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh. A large number of pilgrims visit every day to take a sacred bath in holy Saryu waters.The river front brings forth a majestic landscape specially in floodlit night.There were enormous bathing ghats throughout the banks of the holy river Sarayu and the ones at Nayaghat were immersed in the heavy rains and floods. These were rebuilt in 1985.On occasion of Deepawali in 2019 Ayodhya created Guinness world record by lighting 450k Lamp on Ram ki Paidi.
-Nnx1Dorpn2nNEWl5-vC.name: Ram Ki Paidi

-Nnx3T0psjgCmzxKrpOH.address: Q4RH+6V3, Faizabad Cantt, Faizabad, Uttar Pradesh 224001
-Nnx3T0psjgCmzxKrpOH.description: Situated in the middle of a beautiful and well-kept garden, Military Mahadeva Temple is a prime attraction in Belgaum and also one of the city's oldest temples. The sanctum sanctorum of the temple houses a large image of Lord Shiva along with a shivling. Two Nandi (bull god) idols can also be seen in front of the shivling. The foundation stone of the temple was laid in 1954 and it was made open to public in 1955 by Lieutenant General SM Shrinagesh of the Indian Army. The temple has undergone several renovations and a new dome was built keeping the original style intact. The temple boasts intricate carvings that are similar to the carvings found in prominent temples across South India. It has for long been used as a place of worship by Army personnel, which is why it is called the Military Mahadeva Temple. Devotees can also visit a mini zoo nearby that houses deer and emus. The temple can be visited on all days of the week from 6 am to 8 pm.
-Nnx3T0psjgCmzxKrpOH.name: Military Temple

-Nnx48IwjUsVeBaCs2Fe.description: Ayodhya is the place where 18 ‘Kalyanak’ of different ‘tirthankars’ have taken place. Five Thirthankars were born and preached their religious values here, they include Adinath, Ajitnath, Abhinandannath, Sumatinath, Ananthnath. Kesari Singh, the treasurer of Nawab of Faizabad, got the five Jain shrines constructed to mark the birth place of these Thirthankers. This temple of Digamber Jain sect is dedicated to first Tirthanker Rishabhdev, who is also known as Adinath, Purdev, Vrishabhdev and Adi Brahma.This magnificent, majestic new temple popularly known as Badi Murti is situated in Raiganj locality of Ayodhya. Here a 31 feet high marble statue of Rishabhdev is installed. This place has been recently developed with the blessings of Acharya ratna Deshbhushanji Maharaj and Aryika Gyanmati Mataji.
-Nnx48IwjUsVeBaCs2Fe.name: Jain Temple

-Nnx6M_hpG7KevywrwdZ.address: Q6X6+WX3, Parikrama Marg, Karsewakpuram, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-Nnx6M_hpG7KevywrwdZ.description: The temple is located on a higher ground in Sankat Mochan, Vasudev Ghat, near bye pass in Ayodhya, U. P. It has a huge entrance gate and can be approached by a flight of steps. A large Hanuman idol is installed in the sanctum. Ramnavami, Hanuman Jayanti, Kartik fair, Janmashtami & Basant Panchami are celebrated and Ramayan Path is also organized here regularly.
-Nnx6M_hpG7KevywrwdZ.name: Sankat Mochan Hanuman Mandir / Sankat Mochan Hanuman Kila

-NnxOVmG3hC_Rr7aML1s.address: Adarsh Nagar, Shakti Nagar Colony, Faizabad, Uttar Pradesh 224001
-NnxOVmG3hC_Rr7aML1s.description: The Badi Deokaali Temple is an ancient temple dedicated to Goddess in Faizabad, Uttar Pradesh. The temple is extremely important and is thought to be the Kuldevi (family goddess) of Lord Rama. The temple draws devotees from all over the world because of its rich historical background, unique architecture, and spiritual significance. History of the temple  History of Deokaali Temple Ayodhya The Badi Deokaali Temple has a long history dating back to the Treta Yuga. According to mythology, Maharaja Raghu built and worshipped at the temple during this period. The temple rose to prominence when Lord Rama's mother, Kaushalya, brought him here to see Goddess Devkali after his birth. For generations, the temple has been a place of worship and reverence, with Lord Rama and his ancestors also worshipping there. Significance of the temple  For devotees, Shri Ram's Kuldevi Badi Deokaali Temple is of utmost importance. Worshipping Goddess Devkali is thought to bring protection from evil, salvation, ego destruction, and liberation. It is known as Lord Rama's Kuldevi temple, which adds to its spiritual significance. Architecture of the temple  The temple is entirely made of marble. A large heavy brass bell hangs at the main gate before entering the sanctum sanctorum. The red flag of the mother waves from a dome that is built on top of the temple's circular sanctum sanctorum. The sanctum sanctorum houses the idol of Goddess Devkali, which is considered extraordinary due to the convergence of three superpowers. The idols of Mahalakshmi, Mahakali, and Mahasaraswati are enshrined together, creating a one-of-a-kind sight.
-NnxOVmG3hC_Rr7aML1s.name: Badi Devkali Devi Temple

-NnxPp8xevfhbtSdnFZ1.address: Janki Ghat, Karsewakpuram, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-NnxPp8xevfhbtSdnFZ1.description: Shri Ram Vallabha Kunj at Janaki Ghat Ayodhya is a prominent temple in the city of Ayodhya. It is near Chhoti Chhawni, this temple draws a significant number of tourists each year. It is famous for its iconic images of Shri Ram and Sita with golden crowns, earning it the popular nickname “Sri Vedanti Ji's place.
-NnxPp8xevfhbtSdnFZ1.name: Janki Ghat

-NnxUDcWGJcbCr1rwBoG.address: R622+3M4, Matgajendra Chauraha, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh
-NnxUDcWGJcbCr1rwBoG.description: Matgajendra Temple is a unique and fascinating temple dedicated to Lord Matgajendra, a mythical elephant associated with Lord Vishnu. Located in the holy city of Ayodhya, just about a kilometer from the Ram Janmabhoomi site, this temple holds a special place in the hearts of devotees.  Here's what makes Matgajendra Temple special:      Unique Deity: Unlike most temples in Ayodhya, which are dedicated to Lord Rama or his associates, Matgajendra Temple focuses on a lesser-known but equally significant figure from Hindu mythology. Lord Matgajendra, a mighty elephant, is revered for his unwavering devotion to Lord Vishnu and his miraculous rescue from the clutches of a crocodile.      Ancient Origins: While the exact date of construction remains a mystery, the temple is believed to be centuries old, adding to its aura of mystique and historical significance.      Simple Architecture: In contrast to the grandeur of many other Ayodhya temples, Matgajendra Temple boasts a humble and understated architecture. The small, single-storey structure with a traditional red sandstone facade exudes a sense of intimacy and serenity.      Special Rituals: One of the most intriguing aspects of Matgajendra Temple is the unique tradition of offering green chickpeas as prasad (offering) to the deity. It's believed that Lord Matgajendra was fond of chickpeas, and devotees continue to honor this preference by offering them during prayers.      Festivals and Celebrations: The temple comes alive during the annual "Budhwa Mangalwar," which falls on the first Tuesday after Holi. Devotees throng the temple grounds to offer prayers, participate in special pujas, and partake in the prasad of green chickpeas.      Local Significance: Beyond its religious significance, Matgajendra Temple holds a special place in the hearts of Ayodhya locals. It's considered a guardian deity of the city, and many believe that offering prayers at the temple brings good luck and prosperity.  Visiting Matgajendra Temple:      The temple is open to the public throughout the year.     Entry is free, and visitors can spend time praying, meditating, or simply soaking in the peaceful atmosphere.     Photography is allowed inside the temple premises.
-NnxUDcWGJcbCr1rwBoG.name: Matgajendra Mandir

-NnxXPy2KiSamecT4lEk.address: R654+C68, Theri Bazar, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-NnxXPy2KiSamecT4lEk.description: Shri Kale Ram Temple is located in the city of Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh. The Temple is dedicated to Lord Ram. King Vikramaditya built the Ram temple on Ram ki Paidi 2000 years ago after restoring the Kaleram temple. In 1528 A.D. Babur invaded and fought a holy being named Shyamanand Saraswati. Shyamanand saved an idol from the Mughals and threw it in the Saryu River. The idol stayed there for 220 years. In 1748 A.D. A Brahmin from Maharashtra found it while bathing and brought it to the Kale Ram temple.
-NnxXPy2KiSamecT4lEk.name: Sri Kaleram ji Ka Mandir

-NnxZ-LyHWQ83WPNsFCO.address: Q6V2+M5V, near birla dharamshala, Sai Nagar, Ayodhya, Uttar Pradesh 224123
-NnxZ-LyHWQ83WPNsFCO.description: The temple is dedicated to Lord Rama and Goddess Sita and is also known as Ram Janaki Birla Mandir.  Significance:  The temple is a major tourist attraction for both domestic and international visitors and is an important pilgrimage site for Hindus.  History:  The temple was built by the Birla family, who have built several Birla temples across India. A dharamshala (pilgrim rest house) was also constructed near the temple for the convenience of devotees.  Architecture:  The temple is built in the Hindu Nagara style and is a beautiful example of intricate carvings and architecture. The main deities of the temple are Rama, Sita, and Lakshmana. The temple complex also houses a dharamshala known as Birla Dharamshala.  Importance:  The Birla Mandir holds great importance in Hindu spirituality. It is believed that any devotee who visits the Ram Janmabhoomi (birthplace of Rama) must also visit this temple. The temple provides information about Rama's exile and the Ramayana, as well as insights into Hindu mythology. Birla temples are known for their unique design, which allows them to accommodate a large number of visitors. The Birla Dharamshala is considered to be one of the best and most affordable dharamshalas in Ayodhya, offering excellent facilities to pilgrims.
-NnxZ-LyHWQ83WPNsFCO.name: Sri Ram Janki Birla Temple

-NnxZxCdZnMmi1cPJ9aU.description: Makhauda Dham is one of the most ancient places of Harraiya tehsil in  district where Raja Dashrath performed yagya with the help of Sage Rishyasringa on the advice of Vashistha. Name of Yajna was the Putrakameshti. It is said that Dasharatha and Kaushalya has a daughter Shanta, who was Rishyashringa’s wife. As the conclusion of the Yagya drew near Agni sprang out from the yagnakunda (sacrificial fire pit) and handed Dasharatha a pot of kheer advising him to distribute it among his queens. Kaushalya ate half the kheer, Sumitra ate a quarter of it. Kaikeyi ate some and passed the pot back to Sumitra who consumed the kheer a second time.  Thus the princes were conceived after the consumption of the kheer. Since Kaushalya had consumed the largest portion she gave birth to Rama. Kaikeyi gave birth to Bharata. Sumitra gave birth to Lakshmana and Shatrughna. there.  Ramrekha Mandir is also near a famous historical place Amorha also called place of Raja Zalim Singh’s State Amorha(also known as Amodha) in Basti district of the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
-NnxZxCdZnMmi1cPJ9aU.name: Makhauda Dham

People visits this place specially on Saturday Because it is said that any person who worship here can get rid of shani's Saadhesati so if you are in Ayodhya and want to visit a tretayug's monument Visit here
